# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dynamical-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] In the mathematical field of dynamical systems, an **attractor** is a set of states toward which a system tends to evolve, for a wide variety of starting conditions of the system.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] System values that get close enough to the attractor values remain close even if slightly disturbed.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] In finite-dimensional systems, the evolving variable may be represented algebraically as an *n*-dimensional vector.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The attractor is a region in *n*-dimensional space.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] In physical systems, the *n* dimensions may be, for example, two or three positional coordinates for each of one or more physical entities; in economic systems, they may be separate variables such as the inflation rate and the unemployment rate.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] If the evolving variable is two- or three-dimensional, the attractor of the dynamic process can be represented geometrically in two or three dimensions, (as for example in the three-dimensional case depicted to the right).
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] An attractor can be a point, a finite set of points, a curve, a manifold, or even a complicated set with a fractal structure known as a *strange attractor* (see strange attractor below).
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] If the variable is a scalar, the attractor is a subset of the real number line.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Describing the attractors of chaotic dynamical systems has been one of the achievements of chaos theory.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] A trajectory of the dynamical system in the attractor does not have to satisfy any special constraints except for remaining on the attractor, forward in time.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The trajectory may be periodic or chaotic.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] If a set of points is periodic or chaotic, but the flow in the neighborhood is away from the set, the set is not an attractor, but instead is called a *repeller* (or *repellor*).
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] A dynamical system is generally described by one or more differential or difference equations.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The equations of a given dynamical system specify its behavior over any given short period of time.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] To determine the system's behavior for a longer period, it is often necessary to integrate the equations, either through analytical means or through iteration, often with the aid of computers.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Dynamical systems in the physical world tend to arise from dissipative systems: if it were not for some driving force, the motion would cease.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] (Dissipation may come from internal friction, thermodynamic losses, or loss of material, among many causes.) The dissipation and the driving force tend to balance, killing off initial transients and settle the system into its typical behavior.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The subset of the phase space of the dynamical system corresponding to the typical behavior is the attractor, also known as the attracting section or attractee.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Invariant sets and limit sets are similar to the attractor concept.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] An *invariant set* is a set that evolves to itself under the dynamics.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] A *limit set* is a set of points such that there exists some initial state that ends up arbitrarily close to the limit set (i.e. to each point of the set) as time goes to infinity.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Attractors are limit sets, but not all limit sets are attractors: It is possible to have some points of a system converge to a limit set, but different points when perturbed slightly off the limit set may get knocked off and never return to the vicinity of the limit set.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] For example, the damped pendulum has two invariant points: the point *x*0 of minimum height and the point *x*1 of maximum height.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The point x0 is also a limit set, as trajectories converge to it; the point *x*1 is not a limit set.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Because of the dissipation due to air resistance, the point x0 is also an attractor.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] If there was no dissipation, *x*0 would not be an attractor.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Aristotle believed that objects moved only as long as they were pushed, which is an early formulation of a dissipative attractor.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Some attractors are known to be chaotic (see strange attractor), in which case the evolution of any two distinct points of the attractor result in exponentially diverging trajectories, which complicates prediction when even the smallest noise is present in the system.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Let t represent time and let $f(t,\cdot )$ be a function which specifies the dynamics of the system.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] That is, if a is a point in an n -dimensional phase space, representing the initial state of the system, then $f(0,a)=a$ and, for a positive value of t , $f(t,a)$ is the result of the evolution of this state after t units of time.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Since the basin of attraction contains an open set containing A , every point that is sufficiently close to A is attracted to A .
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The definition of an attractor uses a metric on the phase space, but the resulting notion usually depends only on the topology of the phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] In the case of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , the Euclidean norm is typically used.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Many other definitions of attractor occur in the literature.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] For example, some authors require that an attractor have positive measure (preventing a point from being an attractor), others relax the requirement that $B(A)$ be a neighborhood.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Attractors are portions or subsets of the phase space of a dynamical system.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Until the 1960s, attractors were thought of as being simple geometric subsets of the phase space, like points, lines, surfaces, and simple regions of three-dimensional space.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] More complex attractors that cannot be categorized as simple geometric subsets, such as topologically wild sets, were known of at the time but were thought to be fragile anomalies.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Stephen Smale was able to show that his horseshoe map was robust and that its attractor had the structure of a Cantor set.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Two simple attractors are a fixed point and the limit cycle.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Attractors can take on many other geometric shapes (phase space subsets).
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] But when these sets (or the motions within them) cannot be easily described as simple combinations (e.g. intersection and union) of fundamental geometric objects (e.g. lines, surfaces, spheres, toroids, manifolds), then the attractor is called a *strange attractor*.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] A fixed point of a function or transformation is a point that is mapped to itself by the function or transformation.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] If we regard the evolution of a dynamical system as a series of transformations, then there may or may not be a point which remains fixed under each transformation.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] But the fixed point(s) of a dynamic system is not necessarily an attractor of the system.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] For example, if the bowl containing a rolling marble was inverted and the marble was balanced on top of the bowl, the center bottom (now top) of the bowl is a fixed state, but not an attractor.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] This is equivalent to the difference between stable and unstable equilibria.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] In the case of a marble on top of an inverted bowl (a hill), that point at the top of the bowl (hill) is a fixed point (equilibrium), but not an attractor (unstable equilibrium).
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] In the case of a marble on top of an inverted bowl, even if the bowl seems perfectly hemispherical, and the marble's spherical shape, are both much more complex surfaces when examined under a microscope, and their shapes change or deform during contact.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Any physical surface can be seen to have a rough terrain of multiple peaks, valleys, saddle points, ridges, ravines, and plains.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] There are many points in this surface terrain (and the dynamic system of a similarly rough marble rolling around on this microscopic terrain) that are considered stationary or fixed points, some of which are categorized as attractors.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] In a discrete-time system, an attractor can take the form of a finite number of points that are visited in sequence.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Each of these points is called a periodic point.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] This is illustrated by the logistic map, which depending on its specific parameter value can have an attractor consisting of 1 point, 2 points, 2*n* points, 3 points, 3×2*n* points, 4 points, 5 points, or any given positive integer number of points.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] A limit cycle is a periodic orbit of a continuous dynamical system that is isolated.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Examples include the swings of a pendulum clock, and the heartbeat while resting.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] For a physical pendulum under friction, the resting state will be a fixed-point attractor.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The difference with the clock pendulum is that there, energy is injected by the escapement mechanism to maintain the cycle.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] There may be more than one frequency in the periodic trajectory of the system through the state of a limit cycle.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] For example, in physics, one frequency may dictate the rate at which a planet orbits a star while a second frequency describes the oscillations in the distance between the two bodies.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] If two of these frequencies form an irrational fraction (i.e. they are incommensurate), the trajectory is no longer closed, and the limit cycle becomes a limit torus.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] This kind of attractor is called an *N**t* -torus if there are Nt incommensurate frequencies.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] A time series corresponding to this attractor is a quasiperiodic series: A discretely sampled sum of Nt periodic functions (not necessarily sine waves) with incommensurate frequencies.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Such a time series does not have a strict periodicity, but its power spectrum still consists only of sharp lines.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] An attractor is called *strange* if it has a fractal structure; that is, if it has non-integer Hausdorff dimension.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] This is often the case when the dynamics on it are chaotic, but strange nonchaotic attractors also exist.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Thus a dynamic system with a chaotic attractor is locally unstable yet globally stable: once some sequences have entered the attractor, nearby points diverge from one another but never depart from the attractor.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The term *strange attractor* was coined by David Ruelle and Floris Takens to describe the attractor resulting from a series of bifurcations of a system describing fluid flow.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Strange attractors are often differentiable in a few directions, but some are like a Cantor dust, and therefore not differentiable.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Strange attractors may also be found in the presence of noise, where they may be shown to support invariant random probability measures of Sinai–Ruelle–Bowen type.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Examples of strange attractors include the double-scroll attractor, Hénon attractor, Rössler attractor, and Lorenz attractor.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The behavior of a dynamical system may be influenced by its parameters or the choice of initial conditions.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The logistic map, defined as $x_{n+1}=rx_{n}(1-x_{n})$ , is a well-studied example of a system dependent on one parameter r .
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Its attractors for various values of r are shown in the figure.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] For small r the attractor is a single fixed point, which is shown on the bifurcation diagram as one line.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] For other choices of r , more than one value of x may become attracting: at $r\approx 3$ the fixed point splits in two creating a period 2 cycle during a period-doubling bifurcation.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] As r increases, chaos emerges through a period-doubling cascade, meaning the attractor consists of an infinte number of points.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] At $r\approx 3.83$ a period 3 orbit can be found.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] It follows from the Sharkovskii's theorem that orbits of any natural period are present in the system.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Thus one dynamic equation can have vastly different attractors depending on the choice of parameters.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] An attractor's basin of attraction is the region of the phase space, over which iterations are defined, such that any point (any initial condition) in that region will asymptotically be iterated into the attractor.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] For a stable linear system, every point in the phase space is in the basin of attraction.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] However, in nonlinear systems, some points may map directly or asymptotically to infinity, while other points may lie in a different basin of attraction and map asymptotically into a different attractor; other initial conditions may be in or map directly into a non-attracting point or cycle.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] A univariate linear homogeneous difference equation $x_{t}=ax_{t-1}$ diverges to infinity if $|a|>1$ from all initial points except 0; there is no attractor and therefore no basin of attraction.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] But if $|a|<1$ all points on the number line map asymptotically (or directly in the case of 0) to 0; 0 is the attractor, and the entire number line is the basin of attraction.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] But if the largest eigenvalue is less than 1 in magnitude, all initial vectors will asymptotically converge to the zero vector, which is the attractor; the entire n -dimensional space of potential initial vectors is the basin of attraction.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Similar features apply to linear differential equations.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The scalar equation $dx/dt=ax$ causes all initial values of x except zero to diverge to infinity if $a>0$ but to converge to an attractor at the value 0 if $a<0$ , making the entire number line the basin of attraction for 0.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] And the matrix system $dX/dt=AX$ gives divergence from all initial points except the vector of zeroes if any eigenvalue of the matrix A is positive; but if all the eigenvalues are negative the vector of zeroes is an attractor whose basin of attraction is the entire phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Equations or systems that are nonlinear can give rise to a richer variety of behavior than can linear systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] One example is Newton's method of iterating to a root of a nonlinear expression.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] If the expression has more than one real root, some starting points for the iterative algorithm will lead to one of the roots asymptotically, and other starting points will lead to another.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The basins of attraction for the expression's roots are generally not simple—it is not simply that the points nearest one root all map there, giving a basin of attraction consisting of nearby points.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The basins of attraction can be infinite in number and arbitrarily small.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Newton's method can also be applied to complex functions to find their roots.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Each root has a basin of attraction in the complex plane; these basins can be mapped as in the image shown.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] As can be seen, the combined basin of attraction for a particular root can have many disconnected regions.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] For many complex functions, the boundaries of the basins of attraction are fractals.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] Parabolic partial differential equations may have finite-dimensional attractors.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The diffusive part of the equation damps higher frequencies and in some cases leads to a global attractor.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] The *Ginzburg–Landau*, the *Kuramoto–Sivashinsky*, and the two-dimensional, forced Navier–Stokes equations are all known to have global attractors of finite dimension.
[src:dynamical-systems/attractor] For the three-dimensional, incompressible Navier–Stokes equation with periodic boundary conditions, if it has a global attractor, then this attractor will be of finite dimensions.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In mathematics, physics, engineering and systems theory, a **dynamical system** is the description of how a system evolves in time.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] For example, an astronomer can experimentally record the positions of how the planets move in the sky, and this can be considered a complete enough description of a dynamical system.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In the case of planets there is also enough knowledge to codify this information as a set of differential equations with initial conditions, or as a map from the present state to a future state in a predefined state space with a time parameter t, or as an orbit in phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The study of dynamical systems is the focus of *dynamical systems theory*, which has applications to a wide variety of fields such as mathematics, physics, biology, chemistry, engineering, economics, history, and medicine.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Dynamical systems are a fundamental part of chaos theory, logistic map dynamics, bifurcation theory, the self-assembly and self-organization processes, and the edge of chaos concept.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The concept of a dynamical system has its origins in Newtonian mechanics and more precisely in celestial mechanics.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] There, as in other natural sciences and engineering disciplines, there is some need to predict the evolution of the system, but maybe also pose other questions such as stability, qualitative or long term behaviour, dependence on parameters, existence of periodic, stochastic or chaotic behaviour.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The relation from one state and another is either explicit such as a function in the parameter t predicting position and velocity of a particle or implicit such as a differential equation, difference equation or other time scale.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Some times it may not be possible to define such a description, there may not even be a differential equation predicting stock price, or it maybe impossible to build one but still talk stock prices can be considered a dynamical system based on experimental data changing over time.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Important properties are existence and uniqueness of solutions, integrability (i.e. the existence of conserved quantities), the possibility to solve the system and be able to compute the state at any point in time.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Other properties are whether the system is discrete, continuous, differentiable, smooth, deterministic, ergodic, stochastic or chaotic.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] If the system can be solved, then, given an initial point, it is possible to determine all its future positions, a collection of points known as a *trajectory* or *orbit*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Before the advent of computers, finding an orbit required sophisticated mathematical techniques and could be accomplished only for a small class of dynamical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Numerical methods implemented on electronic computing machines have simplified the task of determining the orbits of a dynamical system.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] For simple dynamical systems, knowing the trajectory is often sufficient, but most dynamical systems are too complicated to be understood in terms of individual trajectories.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Simple examples include the mathematical models that describe the swinging of a clock pendulum, the flow of water in a pipe, the random motion of particles in the air, and the number of fish each springtime in a lake.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Many people regard French mathematician Henri Poincaré as the founder of dynamical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Poincaré published two now classical monographs, "New Methods of Celestial Mechanics" (1892–1899) and "Lectures on Celestial Mechanics" (1905–1910).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In them, he successfully applied the results of their research to the problem of the motion of three bodies and studied in detail the behavior of solutions (frequency, stability, asymptotic, and so on).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] These papers included the Poincaré recurrence theorem, which states that certain systems will, after a sufficiently long but finite time, return to a state very close to the initial state.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Aleksandr Lyapunov developed many important approximation methods.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] His methods, which he developed in 1899, make it possible to define the stability of sets of ordinary differential equations.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] He created the modern theory of the stability of a dynamical system.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In 1913, George David Birkhoff proved Poincaré's "Last Geometric Theorem", a special case of the three-body problem, a result that made him world-famous.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In 1927, he published his *Dynamical Systems*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Birkhoff's most durable result has been his 1931 discovery of what is now called the ergodic theorem.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Combining insights from physics on the ergodic hypothesis with measure theory, this theorem solved, at least in principle, a fundamental problem of statistical mechanics.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The ergodic theorem has also had repercussions for dynamics.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Stephen Smale made significant advances as well.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] His first contribution was the Smale horseshoe that jumpstarted significant research in dynamical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] He also outlined a research program carried out by many others.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Oleksandr Mykolaiovych Sharkovsky developed Sharkovsky's theorem on the periods of discrete dynamical systems in 1964.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] One of the implications of the theorem is that if a discrete dynamical system on the real line has a periodic point of period 3, then it must have periodic points of every other period.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In the late 20th century, the dynamical system perspective to partial differential equations started gaining popularity.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Nayfeh applied nonlinear dynamics in mechanical and engineering systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] His pioneering work in applied nonlinear dynamics has been influential in the construction and maintenance of machines and structures that are common in daily life, such as ships, cranes, bridges, buildings, skyscrapers, jet engines, rocket engines, aircraft and spacecraft.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The most general definition unifies several concepts in mathematics such as ordinary differential equations and ergodic theory, physics such as Phase space, quantum state and thermodynamic state, engineering such as system theory, control theory and even information theory.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] From a mathematics perspective in the most general case the state space X is treated as a generic set of abstract algebra.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] This space X has a semi-group structure on it (i.e. where only associativity is required) and there is most often a natural choice for an Identity element, which is typically attached to the origin of the chosen reference frame.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] This semi-group can be intuitively interpreted as the time coordinate t.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Time in fact has an addition operation and an origin, the identity, like a group.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The action of the semi-group on X is a set of maps from X to itself parametric in the time t, and this is intuitively the time evolution.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Other choices can be a Phase space, a Configuration space or even a discrete space (e.g. the set of prime numbers or a finite field).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Time can be generalized too as a generic set of continuous parameters, for example the control parameters of a robot can be a manifold.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] There is no need that time has a direction, that is smooth or even that it has whatsoever meaning similar to the intuition of time, in fact it can be generalized to even more general algebraic objects.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] A general class of systems are defined over multiple independent variables and are therefore called multidimensional systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Such systems are useful for modeling, and for example in image processing.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Time typically is considered often an external parameter as in classical and quantum mechanics, and this is typically called time domain representation, and it goes hand in hand with the Hamiltonian mechanics formulation.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] This is not necessarily always the case: general relativity for example is frame independent, and gravity has an influence over time too, and in quantum electrodynamics the use of the Lagrangian mechanics formulation is more common where time and space are on same footing.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In both cases the literature still talks about dynamical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] When time is generalized to the multi-dimensional case, i.e. as a general set of control or external parameters, this space can be interpreted as a Lattice, i.e. as the discrete points of a manifold or the tics of a stock price.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Discrete Time events therefore can be counted by integers, for example like the measurements of the position of the planets in the sky, but this can vastly differ from the intuition of time as a clock that has equispaced time events.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] One of the tasks is typically to extract some mathematical model from the data.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The *evolution rule* of the dynamical system is a function that describes what future states follow from the current state.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Often the function is deterministic, that is, for a given time interval only one future state follows from the current state.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] However, some systems are not deterministic they may allow multiple future states (i.e. the maps are generalized into multivalued functions and not uniquely defined everywhere) and the system can be subject to a bifurcation.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Some systems are also stochastic, either in the input parameters such as an oscillator with a random force, or in the initial conditions, or in the predicted variables as in a Stochastic differential equation.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In that random events also affect the evolution of the state variables, and this includes stochastic jump processes which are not continuous, a prototype example of a stochastic dynamical system are stock prices.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] And quantum systems (i.e. deterministic until they are measured), or quantum chaotic systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Assume that X is a non empty set with elements called states.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] It is possible to interpret X as a state space and T as the evolution between states.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Adding different structures on T and on X allows to model different properties of the dynamical system.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] It is possible to model time evolution: ${\hat {T}}$ can be a semigroup with one parameter t called time that will also belong to a semi-group such as $N(t>0)$ in the discrete time case, $R^{+}(t>0)$ in the continuous time case.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] A *real dynamical system*, *real-time dynamical system*, *continuous time dynamical system*, or *flow* is a tuple (*T*, *M*, Φ) with *T* an open interval in the real numbers **R**, *M* a manifold typically but not necessarily locally homeomorphic to a Banach space, and Φ a continuous function.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Being locally homeomorphic to a Banach space allows to use theorems of existence and uniqueness of solutions for differential equations, and linear operators,and this makes it analogous the classical definition based on a system of differential equations.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] If Φ is continuously differentiable the system is called a *differentiable dynamical system*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The function *f* is therefore a "smooth" mapping of the time-domain ${\mathcal {T}}$ into the space of diffeomorphisms of the manifold to itself.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In other terms, *f*(*t*) is a diffeomorphism, for every time *t* in the domain ${\mathcal {T}}$ The manifold *M* is then typically locally diffeomorphic to a Banach space.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] If the manifold *M* is locally diffeomorphic to **R***n*, the dynamical system is *finite-dimensional*; if not, the dynamical system is *infinite-dimensional*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] When *T* is taken to be the reals, the dynamical system is called *global* or a *flow*; and if *T* is restricted to the non-negative reals, then the dynamical system is a *semi-flow*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The modern geometrical definition assumes a map that provides an explicit description of the dynamical system, this is motivated by ergodic theory, by partial differential equations and by mathematical techniques that go beyond differential equations.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] ${\frac {dx_{i}}{dt}}=u_{i}(x_{1},...,x_{n},t);(i=1,...,n)$ There can be different regularity conditions to the functions $u_{i}$ such as being differentiable or analytic.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] This definition implies the existence and uniqueness of solutions of such equations.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Dually to the Lagrangian it is possible to use a Hamiltonian formulation which includes a Symplectic or Poisson manifold structure on the phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] To be complete there are also systems that are typically not integrable systems such as dissipative systems, nonholonomic systems and systems that have a contact manifold structure for example systems that have a no slip boundary condition (i.e. some constraint on the velocity on the boundary).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] An important class of systems from a mathematical perspective is when the map f is algebraic or in general when the map is implicitly defined by a set of algebraic equations and the manifold ${\mathcal {M}}$ is ideally defined on a generic field.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] A *discrete-time dynamical system* is a tuple (*T*, *M*, Φ), where *M* is a manifold locally diffeomorphic to a Banach space, and Φ is a function.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] *T* can be taken to be the integers or the non negative integers.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The manifold itself can be a graph or made discrete for example with a discrete topology.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] A dynamical system may be defined formally as the triplet (*T*, ${\mathfrak {M}}$ , Φ), where Φ is a measure-preserving transformation of a measure space ${\mathfrak {M}}$ , Φ is also the action of a semigroup T as the general case.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Here the Measure space ${\mathfrak {M}}$ is defined by the triplet (*X*, Σ, *μ*), where *X* is a set, Σ is a sigma-algebra on *X* and μ is a finite measure on the measurable space (*X*, Σ).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Often ${\mathfrak {M}}$ is a probability space, i.e. a measure space where the total measure of the full space is 1, in other words with a finite and normalized probability measure.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] A map Φ: *X* → *X* is said to be Σ-measurable if and only if, for every σ in Σ, one has $\Phi ^{-1}\sigma \in \Sigma$ .
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] A map Φ is said to **preserve the measure** if and only if, for every *σ* in Σ, one has $\mu (\Phi ^{-1}\sigma )=\mu (\sigma )$ .
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Combining the above, a map Φ is said to be a **measure-preserving transformation of *X***, if it is a map from *X* to itself, it is Σ-measurable, and is measure-preserving.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The triplet (*T*, ${\mathfrak {M}}$ , Φ), with ${\mathfrak {M}}=$ (*X*, Σ, *μ*) for such a Φ, is then defined to be a **measure-preserving dynamical system**.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Mathematics and discrete convention: all maps are defined as the evolution of the state for one time step to the next one, i.e. from $t_{n}\to t_{n+1}$ , or in the continuous case from $t\to t+\delta t$ .
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The maps ${\hat {\Phi }}_{n}:x\in X,x_{n}\to x_{n+1}$ are the same map $\Phi$ for all time steps $t_{n}$ , this can be interpreted also as an iteration over the map ${\hat {\Phi }}_{n}=\Phi ^{n}=\Phi \circ \Phi \circ \dots \circ \Phi$ .
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] This convention is also related to the study of fixed points, and recursion.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In the language of quantum mechanics the infinitesimal generator of time translation $t\to t+\delta t$ is the derivative in time ${\partial }_{t}$ , and also the time evolution operator. .
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The measure theoretical definition assumes the existence of a measure-preserving transformation, in physical terminology the measure is a probability density function over the phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The intuition comes from Hamiltonian systems which are volume preserving.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The fact that the energy is an integral of motion induces volume conservation on the phase space, or incompressibility of the flow, extra integrals of motions induce further foliations on the phase space..
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Another intuition comes from permutations which are "incompressible".
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] One can interpret the set of all possible permutations of a set as the automorphism group induced by the conservation of number of elements of the set.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Many different invariant measures can be associated to any one evolution rule, in the same manner as multiple probability densities can induce the same macro-state.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] If the dynamical system is given by a system of differential equations the appropriate measure must be determined, the symmetries are not explicit and it may not even be possible to define a probability measure in certain patological cases.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] This makes it difficult to develop ergodic theory starting from differential equations, so it becomes convenient to have a dynamical systems-motivated definition within ergodic theory that side-steps the choice of measure and assumes the choice has been made.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] A simple construction (sometimes called the Krylov–Bogolyubov theorem) shows that for a large class of systems it is always possible to construct a measure so as to make the evolution rule of the dynamical system a measure-preserving transformation.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In the construction a given measure of the state space is summed for all future points of a trajectory, assuring the invariance.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Some systems have a natural measure, such as the Liouville measure in Hamiltonian systems, chosen over other invariant measures, such as the measures supported on periodic orbits of the Hamiltonian system.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] For chaotic dissipative systems the choice of invariant measure is technically more challenging.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The measure needs to be supported on the attractor, but attractors have zero Lebesgue measure and the invariant measures must be singular with respect to the Lebesgue measure.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] For hyperbolic dynamical systems, the Sinai–Ruelle–Bowen measures appear to be the natural choice.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] They are constructed on the geometrical structure of stable and unstable manifolds of the dynamical system; they behave physically under small perturbations; and they explain many of the observed statistics of hyperbolic systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] A topological dynamical system is a dynamical system (**T**, *X*, Φ) on a locally compact and/or Hausdorff topological space *X*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] T is a topological isomorphism and therefore a homeomorphism.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Typically the trajectories are differentiable, and the systems are also flows.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] It is often useful to study the continuous extension Φ* of Φ to the one-point compactification *X** of *X*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Even after losing the differential structure of the original system, there are compactness arguments to analyze the new system (**R**, *X**, Φ*).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] This is similar in spirit to Projective geometry where all limit points to infinity are the same point.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Another more general technique is to use Stone–Čech compactification . which is similar in spirit to affine geometry where all limit points at infinity are considered different.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In compact dynamical systems the limit set of any orbit is non-empty, compact and simply connected.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In the context of category theory, categories are always defined together with an Identity map, therefore these definitions are based on monoids instead of semi-groups.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In particular, in the case that $U=T\times X$ we have for every *x* in *X* that $I(x)=T$ and thus that Φ defines a monoid action of *T* on *X*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The function Φ(*t*,*x*) is called the **evolution function** of the dynamical system: it associates to every point *x* in the set *X* a unique image, depending on the variable *t*, called the **evolution parameter**.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] *X* is called **phase space** or **state space**, while the variable *x* represents an **initial state** of the system.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] We often write: $\Phi _{x}(t)\equiv \Phi (t,x)$ $\Phi ^{t}(x)\equiv \Phi (t,x)$ if we take one of the variables as constant.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The function $\Phi _{x}:I(x)\to X$ is called the **flow** through *x* and its graph is called the **trajectory** through *x*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The orbit through *x* is the image of the flow through *x*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] A subset *S* of the state space *X* is called Φ-**invariant** if for all *x* in *S* and all *t* in *T* $\Phi (t,x)\in S.$ Thus, in particular, if *S* is Φ-**invariant**, $I(x)=T$ for all *x* in *S*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] That is, the flow through *x* must be defined for all time for every element of *S*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The concept of *evolution in time* is central to the theory of dynamical systems as seen in the previous sections: the basic reason for this fact is that the starting motivation of the theory was the study of time behavior of classical mechanical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] But a system of ordinary differential equations must be solved before it becomes a dynamic system.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] There is no need for higher order derivatives in the equation, nor for the parameter *t* in *v*(*t*,*x*), because these can be eliminated by considering systems of higher dimensions.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The dynamical system is then (*T*, *M*, Φ).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] This equation is useful when modeling mechanical systems with complicated constraints.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Many of the concepts in dynamical systems can be extended to infinite-dimensional manifolds—those that are locally Banach spaces—in which case the differential equations are partial differential equations.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] A discrete dynamical system is when either time or space or both are discrete.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Typically for both space and time, there is a finite or countable sets of points and bounded maps and operators, that can be manipulated on a computer given some general assumptions on the boundaries.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In the general context of mathematics, it is possible to define the dynamical system as a general discrete map as in the Formal definition.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] A generic sequence is already per se a discrete dynamical system.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Recursion and interation of maps is another such case.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] A prototype of this is the Logistic map.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Typical tasks with experimental data are to derive a mathematical model.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] In the context of Hamiltonian flows, motion itself can be considered a canonical transformation (i.e. ultimately a map) and therefore a discrete set of these in a discrete time interval $\Delta t$ is again a shape of characterization of the full discrete dynamical system.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] There are also cases of dense orbits, where in essence the state phase space is not compact, and unbounded operators, like in quantum mechanics, where the evolution maps are not compact.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] An example of this is a weather forecast of Earth where the data points are separated in space from each other.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The system can be put on a lattice, and formulas can be used to compute and predict certain variables, like in the case of the discretization of Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Discrete dynamical systems are often also called cascades, when the concept of passing over information from one step to the next is predominant.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Typical examples are avalanches and also period doubling cascades.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] When *T* is taken to be the integers, it is a *cascade* or a *map*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] If *T* is restricted to the non-negative integers the system is called a *semi-cascade*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] A *cellular automaton* is a tuple (*T*, *M*, Φ), with *T* a lattice such as the integers or a higher-dimensional integer grid, *M* is a set of functions from an integer lattice (again, with one or more dimensions) to a finite set, and Φ a (locally defined) evolution function.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] As such cellular automata are dynamical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] The lattice in *M* represents the "space" lattice, while the one in *T* represents the "time" lattice.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p01] Some of these are separate subfields in their own right such as number theory or network theory.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Linear dynamical systems are at the heart of any system engineering and system theory curriculum.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Historically linear systems up to the 1970s reflected most of system theory as a whole (i.e. before the widespread availability of computers).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] They include the basic features of any dynamical system, such as attenuation saturation and oscillation, and at least locally they can approximate also any non linear systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Linear dynamical systems can be solved in terms of simple functions such as exponentials and simple trigonometric functions (i.e. complex exponentials), and the behavior of all orbits can be classified.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] In a linear system the phase space is the *N*-dimensional Euclidean space, so any point in phase space can be represented by a vector with *N* numbers.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The analysis of linear systems is also simplified and possible because they satisfy a superposition principle: if *u*(*t*) and *w*(*t*) satisfy a linear differential equation that describe a system, then so will a linear combination $\alpha u(t)+\beta w(t)$ .
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] With superposition is possible to generate new solutions from known ones, therefore is just necessary to classify the fundamental solutions to know all of them.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] For a flow, the vector field v(*x*) is an affine function of the position in the phase space, that is, ${\dot {x}}=v(x)=Ax+b,$ with *A* a matrix, *b* a vector of numbers and *x* the position vector.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The solution to this system can be found by using the superposition principle (linearity).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] When *b* is zero and *A* ≠ 0 the origin is an equilibrium (or singular) point of the flow, that is, if *x*0 = 0, then the orbit remains there.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] When *b* = 0, the eigenvalues of *A* determine the structure of the phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] From the eigenvalues and the eigenvectors of *A* it is possible to determine if an initial point will converge or diverge to the equilibrium point at the origin.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The distance between two different initial conditions in the case *A* ≠ 0 will change exponentially in most cases, either converging exponentially fast towards a point, or diverging exponentially fast.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Linear systems display sensitive dependence on initial conditions in the case of divergence.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] For nonlinear systems this is one of the (necessary but not sufficient) conditions for chaotic behavior.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] A discrete-time, affine dynamical system has the form of a matrix difference equation: $x_{n+1}=Ax_{n}+b,$ with *A* a matrix and *b* a vector.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] As in the continuous case, the change of coordinates *x* → *x* + (1 − *A*) –1*b* removes the term *b* from the equation.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] In the new coordinate system, the origin is a fixed point of the map and the solutions are of the linear system *A* *n**x*0.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The solutions for the map are no longer curves, but points that hop in the phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The orbits are organized in curves, or fibers, which are collections of points that map into themselves under the action of the map.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] As in the continuous case, the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of *A* determine the structure of phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] For example, if *u*1 is an eigenvector of *A*, with a real eigenvalue smaller than one, then the straight lines given by the points along *α* *u*1, with *α* ∈ **R**, is an invariant curve of the map.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Points in this straight line run into the fixed point.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] There are also many other discrete dynamical systems such as Chaotic maps.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] It is in the neighborhood of singular points and periodic orbits that the structure of a phase space of a dynamical system can be well understood.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] In the qualitative study of dynamical systems, the approach is to show that there is a change of coordinates (usually unspecified, but computable) that makes the dynamical system as simple as possible.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] A flow in most small patches of the phase space can be made very simple.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] If *y* is a point where the vector field *v*(*y*) ≠ 0, then there is a change of coordinates for a region around *y* where the vector field becomes a series of parallel vectors of the same magnitude.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] This is known as the rectification theorem.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The *rectification theorem* says that away from singular points the dynamics of a point in a small patch is a straight line.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The patch can sometimes be enlarged by stitching several patches together, and when this works out in the whole phase space *M* the dynamical system is *integrable*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] In most cases the patch cannot be extended to the entire phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] There may be singular points in the vector field (where *v*(*x*) = 0); or the patches may become smaller and smaller as some point is approached.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The more subtle reason is a global constraint, where the trajectory starts out in a patch, and after visiting a series of other patches comes back to the original one.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] If the next time the orbit loops around phase space in a different way, then it is impossible to rectify the vector field in the whole series of patches.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] In general, in the neighborhood of a periodic orbit the rectification theorem cannot be used.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Poincaré developed an approach that transforms the analysis near a periodic orbit to the analysis of a map.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Pick a point *x*0 in the orbit γ and consider the points in phase space in that neighborhood that are perpendicular to *v*(*x*0).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] These points are a Poincaré section *S*(*γ*, *x*0), of the orbit.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The flow now defines a map, the Poincaré map *F* : *S* → *S*, for points starting in *S* and returning to *S*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Not all these points will take the same amount of time to come back, but the times will be close to the time it takes *x*0.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The intersection of the periodic orbit with the Poincaré section is a fixed point of the Poincaré map *F*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] By a translation, the point can be assumed to be at *x* = 0.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] This is known as the conjugation equation.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Finding conditions for this equation to hold has been one of the major tasks of research in dynamical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Poincaré first approached it assuming all functions to be analytic and in the process discovered the non-resonant condition.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] If *λ*1, ..., *λ**ν* are the eigenvalues of *J* they will be resonant if one eigenvalue is an integer linear combination of two or more of the others.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] As terms of the form *λ**i* – Σ (multiples of other eigenvalues) occurs in the denominator of the terms for the function *h*, the non-resonant condition is also known as the small divisor problem.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The results on the existence of a solution to the conjugation equation depend on the eigenvalues of *J* and the degree of smoothness required from *h*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] As *J* does not need to have any special symmetries, its eigenvalues will typically be complex numbers.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] When the eigenvalues of *J* are not in the unit circle, the dynamics near the fixed point *x*0 of *F* is called *hyperbolic* and when the eigenvalues are on the unit circle and complex, the dynamics is called *elliptic*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] In the hyperbolic case, the Hartman–Grobman theorem gives the conditions for the existence of a continuous function that maps the neighborhood of the fixed point of the map to the linear map *J* · *x*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The hyperbolic case is also *structurally stable*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Small changes in the vector field will only produce small changes in the Poincaré map and these small changes will reflect in small changes in the position of the eigenvalues of *J* in the complex plane, implying that the map is still hyperbolic.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The Kolmogorov–Arnold–Moser (KAM) theorem gives the behavior near an elliptic point.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] When the evolution map Φ*t* (or the vector field it is derived from) depends on a parameter μ, the structure of the phase space will also depend on this parameter.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Small changes may produce no qualitative changes in the phase space until a special value *μ*0 is reached.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] At this point the phase space changes qualitatively and the dynamical system is said to have gone through a bifurcation.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Bifurcation theory considers a structure in phase space (typically a fixed point, a periodic orbit, or an invariant torus) and studies its behavior as a function of the parameter *μ*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] At the bifurcation point the structure may change its stability, split into new structures, or merge with other structures.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] By using Taylor series approximations of the maps and an understanding of the differences that may be eliminated by a change of coordinates, it is possible to catalog the bifurcations of dynamical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The bifurcations of a hyperbolic fixed point *x*0 of a system family *Fμ* can be characterized by the eigenvalues of the first derivative of the system *DF**μ*(*x*0) computed at the bifurcation point.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] For a map, the bifurcation will occur when there are eigenvalues of *DFμ* on the unit circle.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] For a flow, it will occur when there are eigenvalues on the imaginary axis.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] For more information, see the main article on Bifurcation theory.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Some bifurcations can lead to very complicated structures in phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] For example, the Ruelle–Takens scenario describes how a periodic orbit bifurcates into a torus and the torus into a strange attractor.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] In another example, Feigenbaum period-doubling describes how a stable periodic orbit goes through a series of period-doubling bifurcations.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] In many dynamical systems, it is possible to choose the coordinates of the system so that the volume (really a ν-dimensional volume) in phase space is invariant.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] This happens for mechanical systems derived from Newton's laws as long as the coordinates are the position and the momentum and the volume is measured in units of (position) × (momentum).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The volume is said to be computed by the Liouville measure.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] In a Hamiltonian system, not all possible configurations of position and momentum can be reached from an initial condition.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Because of energy conservation, only the states with the same energy as the initial condition are accessible.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The states with the same energy form an energy shell Ω, a sub-manifold of the phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The volume of the energy shell, computed using the Liouville measure, is preserved under evolution.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] For systems where the volume is preserved by the flow, Poincaré discovered the recurrence theorem: Assume the phase space has a finite Liouville volume and let *F* be a phase space volume-preserving map and *A* a subset of the phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Then almost every point of *A* returns to *A* infinitely often.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The Poincaré recurrence theorem was used by Zermelo to object to Boltzmann's derivation of the increase in entropy in a dynamical system of colliding atoms.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] One of the questions raised by Boltzmann's work was the possible equality between time averages and space averages, what he called the ergodic hypothesis.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The hypothesis states that the length of time a typical trajectory spends in a region *A* is vol(*A*)/vol(Ω).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The ergodic hypothesis turned out not to be the essential property needed for the development of statistical mechanics and a series of other ergodic-like properties were introduced to capture the relevant aspects of physical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Koopman approached the study of ergodic systems by the use of functional analysis.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] An observable *a* is a function that to each point of the phase space associates a number (say instantaneous pressure, or average height).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The value of an observable can be computed at another time by using the evolution function φ t.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] By studying the spectral properties of the linear operator *U* it becomes possible to classify the ergodic properties of Φ *t*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] In using the Koopman approach of considering the action of the flow on an observable function, the finite-dimensional nonlinear problem involving Φ *t* gets mapped into an infinite-dimensional linear problem involving *U*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The Liouville measure restricted to the energy surface Ω is the basis for the averages computed in equilibrium statistical mechanics.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] An average in time along a trajectory is equivalent to an average in space computed with the Boltzmann factor exp(−β*H*).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] This idea has been generalized by Sinai, Bowen, and Ruelle (SRB) to a larger class of dynamical systems that includes dissipative systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] SRB measures replace the Boltzmann factor and they are defined on attractors of chaotic systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Simple nonlinear dynamical systems, including piecewise linear systems, can exhibit strongly unpredictable behavior, which might seem to be random, despite the fact that they are fundamentally deterministic.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] This unpredictable behavior has been called *chaos*.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Hyperbolic systems are precisely defined dynamical systems that exhibit the properties ascribed to chaotic systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] In hyperbolic systems the tangent spaces perpendicular to an orbit can be decomposed into a combination of two parts: one with the points that converge towards the orbit (the *stable manifold*) and another of the points that diverge from the orbit (the *unstable manifold*).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] This branch of mathematics deals with the long-term qualitative behavior of dynamical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The chaotic behavior of complex systems is not the issue.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Meteorology has been known for years to involve complex—even chaotic—behavior.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Chaos theory has been so surprising because chaos can be found within almost trivial systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The Pomeau–Manneville scenario of the logistic map and the Fermi–Pasta–Ulam–Tsingou problem arose with just second-degree polynomials; the horseshoe map is piecewise linear.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] For non-linear autonomous ODEs it is possible under some conditions to develop solutions of finite duration, meaning here that in these solutions the system will reach the value zero at some time, called an ending time, and then stay there forever after.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] This can occur only when system trajectories are not uniquely determined forwards and backwards in time by the dynamics, thus solutions of finite duration imply a form of "backwards-in-time unpredictability" closely related to the forwards-in-time unpredictability of chaos.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] This behavior cannot happen for Lipschitz continuous differential equations according to the proof of the Picard-Lindelof theorem.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] These solutions are non-Lipschitz functions at their ending times and cannot be analytical functions on the whole real line.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Algebraic dynamical systems can be considered as a special algebraic case of the classical geometric definition.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] This is based on an algebraic time evolution map as the group action or implicitly as a system of algebraic equations instead of ODEs.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] From a measure theoretic perspective, the manifold is a measure space, a variety, an algebraic group, and a topological group: the focus is then on symmetries, and ergodic theory behavior.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] These systems are often studied with methods from abstract algebra, algebraic geometry and Galois theory.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] In the context of Algebraic quantum field theory the measure space can be a C*-algebra, namely observables are not just algebras of functions but an operator algebra, and this is treated together with a global gauge group (i.e. a group of constraints that leaves the observable invariant).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] In the context of machine learning the neural network itself (e.g.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] One such examples is the Poncelet map, where a point is moving in successive steps between two given conics, and the equations are algebraic (i.e. tangents and intersections).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Another example can be a billiard with a border that is an algebraic curve, such as an elliptic billiard, in this case the dynamics is defined by reflections.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Note that algebraic curves are differentiable almost every where (a part from a finite number of points), therefore one can study them with analytic methods.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] These systems can therefore be studied as discrete dynamical systems too.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Effective dynamics is the coarse-graining of equations of motion that describe a system at a certain scale, or a specific behaviour, typically getting rid of certain degrees of freedom.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Instead of solving the microstate, i.e. the exact interactions for all atoms, molecules, or neural network nodes, effective dynamics models an "effective" force, energy or set of parameters and equations that describe the aggregate effect.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Typically effective dynamics arises from simplifying or specializing complex non linear phenomena, a major way to achieve this is with ensemble averages and this links it deeply with Ergodic theory and the Renormalization group.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Examples of these approaches are Effective Field Theories,Reynolds Averaged Navier-Stokes (RANS), disordered quantum systems, thermodynamics and Phase transitions.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] In the period between 2000 and 2020, category theory has been applied to system theory (e.g. to open systems and subsystems) and to dynamical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] The motivation is to study common properties across dynamical systems, topological dynamical systems (i.e. with compact state space), and measure preserving dynamical systems (e.g. hamiltonian systems).
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] It is also possible to draw an analogy between group representation theory (such as irreducible representations) and ergodic decomposition i.e. that every invariant (i.e. conservative) measure is a mixture of ergodic ones, in an analogous fashion to the central limit theorem.
[src:dynamical-systems/dynamical-system-p02] Ultimately this can be compared to the fundamental theorem of arithmetic and to prime number decomposition.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Ergodic theory, like probability theory, is based on general notions of measure theory.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Its initial development was motivated by problems of statistical physics.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] A central concern of ergodic theory is the behavior of a dynamical system when it is allowed to run for a long time.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The first result in this direction is the Poincaré recurrence theorem, which claims that almost all points in any subset of the phase space eventually revisit the set.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Systems for which the Poincaré recurrence theorem holds are conservative systems; thus all ergodic systems are conservative.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] More precise information is provided by various **ergodic theorems** which assert that, under certain conditions, the time average of a function along the trajectories exists almost everywhere and is related to the space average.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Two of the most important theorems are those of Birkhoff (1931) and von Neumann which assert the existence of a time average along each trajectory.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] For the special class of **ergodic systems**, this time average is the same for almost all initial points: statistically speaking, the system that evolves for a long time "forgets" its initial state.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Stronger properties, such as mixing and equidistribution, have also been extensively studied.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The problem of metric classification of systems is another important part of the abstract ergodic theory.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] An outstanding role in ergodic theory and its applications to stochastic processes is played by the various notions of entropy for dynamical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The concepts of ergodicity and the ergodic hypothesis are central to applications of ergodic theory.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The underlying idea is that for certain systems the time average of their properties is equal to the average over the entire space.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Applications of ergodic theory to other parts of mathematics usually involve establishing ergodicity properties for systems of special kind.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] In geometry, methods of ergodic theory have been used to study the geodesic flow on Riemannian manifolds, starting with the results of Eberhard Hopf for Riemann surfaces of negative curvature.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Markov chains form a common context for applications in probability theory.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Ergodic theory has fruitful connections with harmonic analysis, Lie theory (representation theory, lattices in algebraic groups), and number theory (the theory of diophantine approximations, L-functions).
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Ergodic theory is often concerned with **ergodic transformations**.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The intuition behind such transformations, which act on a given set, is that they do a thorough job "stirring" the elements of that set.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] At the same time, these iterations will not compress or dilate any portion of the oatmeal: they preserve the measure that is density.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Let *T* : *X* → *X* be a measure-preserving transformation on a measure space (*X*, *Σ*, *μ*), with *μ*(*X*) = 1.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The operator Δ here is the symmetric difference of sets, equivalent to the exclusive-or operation with respect to set membership.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The condition that the symmetric difference be measure zero is called being **essentially invariant**.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Let *T*: *X* → *X* be a measure-preserving transformation on a measure space (*X*, Σ, *μ*) and suppose *f* is a *μ*-integrable function, i.e.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] In general the time average and space average may be different.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] But if the transformation is ergodic, and the measure is invariant, then the time average is equal to the space average almost everywhere.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] This is the celebrated ergodic theorem, in an abstract form due to George David Birkhoff.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] for almost all *x*, i.e., for all *x* except for a set of measure zero.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] For an ergodic transformation, the time average equals the space average almost surely.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] As an example, assume that the measure space (*X*, Σ, *μ*) models the particles of a gas as above, and let *f*(*x*) denote the velocity of the particle at position *x*.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Then the pointwise ergodic theorems says that the average velocity of all particles at some given time is equal to the average velocity of one particle over time.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] A generalization of Birkhoff's theorem is Kingman's subadditive ergodic theorem.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] where $E(f|{\mathcal {C}})$ is the conditional expectation given the σ-algebra ${\mathcal {C}}$ of invariant sets of *T*.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Let *U* be a unitary operator on a Hilbert space *H*; more generally, an isometric linear operator (that is, a not necessarily surjective linear operator satisfying ‖*Ux*‖ = ‖*x*‖ for all *x* in *H*, or equivalently, satisfying *U***U* = I, but not necessarily *UU** = I).
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Let *P* be the orthogonal projection onto {*ψ* ∈ *H* | *Uψ* = ψ} = ker(*I* − *U*).
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] where the limit is with respect to the norm on *H*.
