[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Indeed, it is not difficult to see that in this case any $x\in H$ admits an orthogonal decomposition into parts from $\ker(I-U)$ and ${\overline {\operatorname {ran} (I-U)}}$ respectively.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] where *T* is a measure-preserving endomorphism of *X*, thought of in applications as representing a time-step of a discrete dynamical system.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The ergodic theorem then asserts that the average behavior of a function ƒ over sufficiently large time-scales is approximated by the orthogonal component of ƒ which is time-invariant.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] In another form of the mean ergodic theorem, let *Ut* be a strongly continuous one-parameter group of unitary operators on *H*.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] converges in the strong operator topology as *T* → ∞.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] In fact, this result also extends to the case of strongly continuous one-parameter semigroup of contractive operators on a reflexive space.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Remark: Some intuition for the mean ergodic theorem can be developed by considering the case where complex numbers of unit length are regarded as unitary transformations on the complex plane (by left multiplication).
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] If we pick a single complex number of unit length (which we think of as *U*), it is intuitive that its powers will fill up the circle.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Since the circle is symmetric around 0, it makes sense that the averages of the powers of *U* will converge to 0.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Also, 0 is the only fixed point of *U*, and so the projection onto the space of fixed points must be the zero operator (which agrees with the limit just described).
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Let (*X*, Σ, *μ*) be as above a probability space with a measure preserving transformation *T*, and let 1 ≤ *p* ≤ ∞.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The conditional expectation with respect to the sub-σ-algebra Σ*T* of the *T*-invariant sets is a linear projector *ET* of norm 1 of the Banach space *Lp*(*X*, Σ, *μ*) onto its closed subspace *Lp*(*X*, Σ*T*, *μ*).
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The latter may also be characterized as the space of all *T*-invariant *Lp*-functions on *X*.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The ergodic means, as linear operators on *Lp*(*X*, Σ, *μ*) also have unit operator norm; and, as a simple consequence of the Birkhoff–Khinchin theorem, converge to the projector *ET* in the strong operator topology of *Lp* if 1 ≤ *p* ≤ ∞, and in the weak operator topology if *p* = ∞.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] More is true if 1 < *p* ≤ ∞ then the Wiener–Yoshida–Kakutani ergodic dominated convergence theorem states that the ergodic means of *f* ∈ *Lp* are dominated in *Lp*; however, if *f* ∈ *L*1, the ergodic means may fail to be equidominated in *Lp*.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Finally, if *f* is assumed to be in the Zygmund class, that is |*f*| log+(|*f*|) is integrable, then the ergodic means are even dominated in *L*1.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Let (*X*, Σ, *μ*) be a measure space such that *μ*(*X*) is finite and nonzero.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The time spent in a measurable set *A* is called the **sojourn time**.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] for all *x* except for a set of measure zero, where χ*A* is the indicator function of *A*.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The **occurrence times** of a measurable set *A* is defined as the set *k*1, *k*2, *k*3, ..., of times *k* such that *Tk*(*x*) is in *A*, sorted in increasing order.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The differences between consecutive occurrence times *Ri* = *ki* − *k**i*−1 are called the **recurrence times** of *A*.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Another consequence of the ergodic theorem is that the average recurrence time of *A* is inversely proportional to the measure of *A*, assuming that the initial point *x* is in *A*, so that *k*0 = 0.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] (See almost surely.) That is, the smaller *A* is, the longer it takes to return to it.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The relation between geodesic flows on Riemann surfaces and one-parameter subgroups on SL(2, **R**) was described in 1952 by S.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] The article on Anosov flows provides an example of ergodic flows on SL(2, **R**) and on Riemann surfaces of negative curvature.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Much of the development described there generalizes to hyperbolic manifolds, since they can be viewed as quotients of the hyperbolic space by the action of a lattice in the semisimple Lie group SO(n,1).
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Ergodicity of the geodesic flow on Riemannian symmetric spaces was demonstrated by F.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Sinai proved ergodicity of the geodesic flow on compact manifolds of variable negative sectional curvature.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] A simple criterion for the ergodicity of a homogeneous flow on a homogeneous space of a semisimple Lie group was given by Calvin C.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Many of the theorems and results from this area of study are typical of rigidity theory.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Hedlund proved that the horocycle flow on a compact hyperbolic surface is minimal and ergodic.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Unique ergodicity of the flow was established by Hillel Furstenberg in 1972.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] Ratner's theorems provide a major generalization of ergodicity for unipotent flows on the homogeneous spaces of the form Γ \ *G*, where *G* is a Lie group and Γ is a lattice in *G*.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] In the last 20 years, there have been many works trying to find a measure-classification theorem similar to Ratner's theorems but for diagonalizable actions, motivated by conjectures of Furstenberg and Margulis.
[src:dynamical-systems/ergodic-theory] An important partial result (solving those conjectures with an extra assumption of positive entropy) was proved by Elon Lindenstrauss, and he was awarded the Fields Medal in 2010 for this result.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] In mathematics, a **fixed point** (sometimes shortened to **fixpoint**), also known as an **invariant point**, is a value that does not change under a given transformation.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] Specifically, for functions, a fixed point is an element that is mapped to itself by the function.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] Any set of fixed points of a transformation is also an invariant set.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] Formally, c is a fixed point of a function f if c belongs to both the domain and the codomain of f, and *f*(*c*) = *c*.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] In particular, f cannot have any fixed point if its domain is disjoint from its codomain.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] If *f* is defined on the real numbers, it corresponds, in graphical terms, to a curve in the Euclidean plane, and each fixed-point *c* corresponds to an intersection of the curve with the line *y* = *x*, cf. picture.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] For example, if *f* is defined on the real numbers by $f(x)=x^{2}-3x+4,$ then 2 is a fixed point of *f*, because *f*(2) = 2.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] Not all functions have fixed points: for example, *f*(*x*) = *x* + 1 has no fixed points because *x* + 1 is never equal to *x* for any real number.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] In numerical analysis, *fixed-point iteration* is a method of computing fixed points of a function.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] which gives rise to the sequence $x_{0},x_{1},x_{2},\dots$ of iterated function applications $x_{0},f(x_{0}),f(f(x_{0})),\dots$ which is hoped to converge to a point x .
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] If f is continuous, then one can prove that the obtained x is a fixed point of f .
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] The notions of attracting fixed points, repelling fixed points, and periodic points are defined with respect to fixed-point iteration.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] A fixed-point theorem is a result saying that at least one fixed point exists, under some general condition.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] For example, the Banach fixed-point theorem (1922) gives a general criterion guaranteeing that, if it is satisfied, fixed-point iteration will always converge to a fixed point.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] The Brouwer fixed-point theorem (1911) says that any continuous function from the closed unit ball in *n*-dimensional Euclidean space to itself must have a fixed point, but it doesn't describe how to find the fixed point.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] The Lefschetz fixed-point theorem (and the Nielsen fixed-point theorem) from algebraic topology give a way to count fixed points.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] In algebra, for a group *G* acting on a set *X* with a group action $\cdot$ , *x* in *X* is said to be a fixed point of *g* if $g\cdot x=x$ .
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] In Galois theory, the set of the fixed points of a set of automorphisms of a field is called the fixed field of the set of automorphisms.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] there exists $x\in X$ such that $f(x)=x$ .
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] The FPP is a topological invariant, i.e., it is preserved by any homeomorphism.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] The FPP is also preserved by any retraction.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] According to the Brouwer fixed-point theorem, every compact and convex subset of a Euclidean space has the FPP.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] Compactness alone does not imply the FPP, and convexity is not even a topological property, so it makes sense to ask how to topologically characterize the FPP.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] In 1932 Borsuk asked whether compactness together with contractibility could be a necessary and sufficient condition for the FPP to hold.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] The problem was open for 20 years until the conjecture was disproved by Kinoshita, who found an example of a compact contractible space without the FPP.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] In domain theory, the notion and terminology of fixed points is generalized to a partial order.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] Let ≤ be a partial order over a set *X* and let *f*: *X* → *X* be a function over *X*.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] Then a **prefixed point** (also spelled **pre-fixed point**, sometimes shortened to **prefixpoint** or **pre-fixpoint**) of *f* is any *p* such that *f*(*p*) ≤ *p*.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] Analogously, a *postfixed point* of *f* is any *p* such that *p* ≤ *f*(*p*).
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] The opposite usage occasionally appears.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] Malkis justifies the definition presented here as follows: "since *f* is *before* the inequality sign in the term *f*(*x*) ≤ *x*, such *x* is called a *pre*fix point." A fixed point is a point that is both a prefixpoint and a postfixpoint.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] Prefixpoints and postfixpoints have applications in theoretical computer science.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] In order theory, the least fixed point of a function from a partially ordered set (poset) to itself is the fixed point which is less than each other fixed point, according to the order of the poset.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] A function need not have a least fixed point, but if it does then the least fixed point is unique.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] One way to express the Knaster–Tarski theorem is to say that a monotone function on a complete lattice has a least fixed point that coincides with its least prefixpoint (and similarly its greatest fixed point coincides with its greatest postfixpoint).
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] In combinatory logic for computer science, a fixed-point combinator is a higher-order function ${\mathsf {fix}}$ that returns a fixed point of its argument function, if one exists.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] In mathematical logic, fixed-point logics are extensions of classical predicate logic that have been introduced to express recursion.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] Their development has been motivated by descriptive complexity theory and their relationship to database query languages, in particular to Datalog.
[src:dynamical-systems/fixed-point-mathematics] In many fields, equilibria or stability are fundamental concepts that can be described in terms of fixed points.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] In physics, **Hamiltonian mechanics** is a reformulation of Lagrangian mechanics that emerged in 1833.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Introduced by Sir William Rowan Hamilton, Hamiltonian mechanics replaces (generalized) velocities ${\dot {q}}^{i}$ used in Lagrangian mechanics with (generalized) *momenta*.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Both theories provide interpretations of classical mechanics and describe the same physical phenomena.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Hamiltonian mechanics has a close relationship with geometry (notably, symplectic geometry and Poisson structures) and serves as a link between classical and quantum mechanics.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] (Also *generalized momenta*, *conjugate momenta*, and *canonical momenta*).
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The Legendre transform of ${\mathcal {L}}$ turns $E_{\mathcal {L}}$ into a function ${\mathcal {H}}({\boldsymbol {p}},{\boldsymbol {q}},t)$ known as the **Hamiltonian**.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The ( $2n$ -dimensional) pair $({\boldsymbol {p}},{\boldsymbol {q}})$ is called *phase space coordinates*.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] By rearranging the equation ${\boldsymbol {p}}=\partial {\mathcal {L}}/\partial {\dot {\boldsymbol {q}}}$ , we can write ${\dot {\boldsymbol {q}}}$ in terms of ${\boldsymbol {q}}$ and ${\boldsymbol {p}}$ as ${\dot {\boldsymbol {q}}}({\boldsymbol {q}},{\boldsymbol {p}})$ .
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] So **1** becomes an equation in two variables: ${\boldsymbol {q}}$ and ${\boldsymbol {p}}$ .
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] A path ${\boldsymbol {q}}\in {\mathcal {P}}(a,b,{\boldsymbol {x}}_{a},{\boldsymbol {x}}_{b})$ is a stationary point of ${\mathcal {S}}$ (and hence is an equation of motion) if and only if the path $({\boldsymbol {p}}(t),{\boldsymbol {q}}(t))$ in phase space coordinates obeys the Hamilton equations.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] A simple interpretation of Hamiltonian mechanics comes from its application on a one-dimensional system consisting of one nonrelativistic particle of mass m.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The value $H(p,q)$ of the Hamiltonian is the total energy of the system, in this case the sum of kinetic and potential energy, traditionally denoted T and V, respectively.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Here p is the momentum mv and q is the space coordinate.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Then ${\mathcal {H}}=T+V,\qquad T={\frac {p^{2}}{2m}},\qquad V=V(q)$ T is a function of p alone, while V is a function of q alone (i.e., T and V are scleronomic).
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] In this example, the time derivative of q is the velocity, and so the first Hamilton equation means that the particle's velocity equals the derivative of its kinetic energy with respect to its momentum.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The time derivative of the momentum p equals the *Newtonian force*, and so the second Hamilton equation means that the force equals the negative gradient of potential energy.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] A spherical pendulum consists of a mass *m* moving without friction on the surface of a sphere.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The only forces acting on the mass are the reaction from the sphere and gravity.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Spherical coordinates are used to describe the position of the mass in terms of (*r*, *θ*, *φ*), where *r* is fixed, *r* = *ℓ*.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] That is a consequence of the rotational symmetry of the system around the vertical axis.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Being absent from the Hamiltonian, azimuth $\varphi$ is a cyclic coordinate, which implies conservation of its conjugate momentum.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Hamilton's equations can be derived by a calculation with the Lagrangian ⁠ ${\mathcal {L}}$ ⁠, generalized positions qi, and generalized velocities ⋅*q**i*, where ⁠ $i=1,\ldots ,n$ ⁠.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Here we work off-shell, meaning ⁠ $q^{i}$ ⁠, ⁠ ${\dot {q}}^{i}$ ⁠, ⁠ t ⁠ are independent coordinates in phase space, not constrained to follow any equations of motion (in particular, ${\dot {q}}^{i}$ is not a derivative of ⁠ $q^{i}$ ⁠).
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] In the case of time-independent ${\mathcal {H}}$ and ⁠ ${\mathcal {L}}$ ⁠, i.e. ⁠ $\partial {\mathcal {H}}/\partial t=-\partial {\mathcal {L}}/\partial t=0$ ⁠, Hamilton's equations consist of 2*n* first-order differential equations, while Lagrange's equations consist of n second-order equations.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Hamilton's equations usually do not reduce the difficulty of finding explicit solutions, but important theoretical results can be derived from them, because coordinates and momenta are independent variables with nearly symmetric roles.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] This effectively reduces the problem from n coordinates to (*n* − 1) coordinates: this is the basis of symplectic reduction in geometry.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] In the Lagrangian framework, the conservation of momentum also follows immediately, however all the generalized velocities ${\dot {q}}_{i}$ still occur in the Lagrangian, and a system of equations in n coordinates still has to be solved.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The Lagrangian and Hamiltonian approaches provide the groundwork for deeper results in classical mechanics, and suggest analogous formulations in quantum mechanics: the path integral formulation and the Schrödinger equation.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] where T is the kinetic energy and V is the potential energy.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Using this relation can be simpler than first calculating the Lagrangian, and then deriving the Hamiltonian from the Lagrangian.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] However, the relation is not true for all systems.
