[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] In words, this means that the relation ${\mathcal {H}}=T+V$ holds true if T does not contain time as an explicit variable (it is scleronomic), V does not contain generalised velocity as an explicit variable, and each term of T is quadratic in generalised velocity.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Preliminary to this proof, it is important to address an ambiguity in the related mathematical notation.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] In this case, the right hand side always evaluates to 0.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] To perform a change of variables inside of a partial derivative, the multivariable chain rule should be used.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Hence, to avoid ambiguity, the function arguments of any term inside of a partial derivative should be stated.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Additionally, this proof uses the notation $f(a,b,c)=f(a,b)$ to imply that ${\frac {\partial f(a,b,c)}{\partial c}}=0$ .
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] where each $c_{ij}({\boldsymbol {q}})$ is an arbitrary scalar function of ${\boldsymbol {q}}$ .
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] This simplification is a result of Euler's homogeneous function theorem.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] For a system of point masses, the requirement for T to be quadratic in generalised velocity is always satisfied for the case where $T({\boldsymbol {q}},{\boldsymbol {\dot {q}}},t)=T({\boldsymbol {q}},{\boldsymbol {\dot {q}}})$ , which is a requirement for ${\mathcal {H}}=T+V$ anyway.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Consider the kinetic energy for a system of N point masses.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] If the conditions for ${\mathcal {H}}=T+V$ are satisfied, then conservation of the Hamiltonian implies conservation of energy.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] This requires the additional condition that V does not contain time as an explicit variable.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Regarding extensions to the Euler-Lagrange formulation which use dissipation functions (See *Lagrangian mechanics § Extensions to include non-conservative forces*), e.g. the Rayleigh dissipation function, energy is not conserved when a dissipation function has effect.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] It is possible to explain the link between this and the former requirements by relating the extended and conventional Euler-Lagrange equations: grouping the extended terms into the potential function produces a velocity dependent potential.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Hence, the requirements are not satisfied when a dissipation function has effect.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] A sufficient illustration of Hamiltonian mechanics is given by the Hamiltonian of a charged particle in an electromagnetic field.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] This Lagrangian, combined with Euler–Lagrange equation, produces the Lorentz force law $m{\ddot {\mathbf {x} }}=q\mathbf {E} +q{\dot {\mathbf {x} }}\times \mathbf {B} \,,$ and is called minimal coupling.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] This equation is used frequently in quantum mechanics.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Under gauge transformation: $\mathbf {A} \rightarrow \mathbf {A} +\nabla f\,,\quad \varphi \rightarrow \varphi -{\dot {f}}\,,$ where *f*(**r**, *t*) is any scalar function of space and time.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] In quantum mechanics, the wave function will also undergo a local U(1) group transformation during the Gauge Transformation, which implies that all physical results must be invariant under local U(1) transformations.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] As a closed nondegenerate symplectic 2-form *ω*.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Due to the bilinearity and non-degeneracy of ⁠ $\omega$ ⁠, and the fact that ⁠ $\dim T_{x}M=\dim T_{x}^{*}M$ ⁠, the mapping $\xi \to \omega _{\xi }$ is indeed a linear isomorphism.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] This isomorphism is *natural* in that it does not change with change of coordinates on $M.$ Repeating over all ⁠ $x\in M$ ⁠, we end up with an isomorphism $J^{-1}:{\text{Vect}}(M)\to \Omega ^{1}(M)$ between the infinite-dimensional space of smooth vector fields and that of smooth 1-forms.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] (In algebraic terms, one would say that the $C^{\infty }(M,\mathbb {R} )$ -modules ${\text{Vect}}(M)$ and $\Omega ^{1}(M)$ are isomorphic).
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The respective differential equation on M ${\dot {x}}=J(dH)(x)$ is called *Hamilton's equation*.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Here $x=x(t)$ and $J(dH)(x)\in T_{x}M$ is the (time-dependent) value of the vector field $J(dH)$ at ⁠ $x\in M$ ⁠.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] A Hamiltonian system may be understood as a fiber bundle E over time R, with the fiber Et being the position space at time *t* ∈ *R*.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The correspondence between Lagrangian and Hamiltonian mechanics is achieved with the tautological one-form.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Any smooth real-valued function H on a symplectic manifold can be used to define a Hamiltonian system.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The function H is known as "the Hamiltonian" or "the energy function." The symplectic manifold is then called the phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The Hamiltonian induces a special vector field on the symplectic manifold, known as the Hamiltonian vector field.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The Hamiltonian vector field induces a Hamiltonian flow on the manifold.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] This is a one-parameter family of transformations of the manifold (the parameter of the curves is commonly called "the time"); in other words, an isotopy of symplectomorphisms, starting with the identity.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] By Liouville's theorem, each symplectomorphism preserves the volume form on the phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The collection of symplectomorphisms induced by the Hamiltonian flow is commonly called "the Hamiltonian mechanics" of the Hamiltonian system.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The symplectic structure induces a Poisson bracket.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The Poisson bracket gives the space of functions on the manifold the structure of a Lie algebra.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] If F and G are smooth functions on M then the smooth function *ω*(*J*(*dF*), *J*(*dG*)) is properly defined; it is called a *Poisson bracket* of functions F and G and is denoted {*F*, *G*}.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] 5. non-degeneracy: if the point x on M is not critical for F then a smooth function G exists such that ⁠ $\{F,G\}(x)\neq 0$ ⁠.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Every smooth function G over the symplectic manifold generates a one-parameter family of symplectomorphisms and if {*G*, *H*} = 0, then G is conserved and the symplectomorphisms are symmetry transformations.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] A Hamiltonian may have multiple conserved quantities *G**i*.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] If the symplectic manifold has dimension 2*n* and there are n functionally independent conserved quantities Gi which are in involution (i.e., {*G**i*, *G**j*} = 0), then the Hamiltonian is Liouville integrable.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The Liouville–Arnold theorem says that, locally, any Liouville integrable Hamiltonian can be transformed via a symplectomorphism into a new Hamiltonian with the conserved quantities Gi as coordinates; the new coordinates are called *action–angle coordinates*.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The transformed Hamiltonian depends only on the *G**i*, and hence the equations of motion have the simple form ${\dot {G}}_{i}=0\quad ,\quad {\dot {\varphi }}_{i}=F_{i}(G)$ for some function F.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] There is an entire field focusing on small deviations from integrable systems governed by the KAM theorem.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The integrability of Hamiltonian vector fields is an open question.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] In general, Hamiltonian systems are chaotic; concepts of measure, completeness, integrability and stability are poorly defined.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] This Hamiltonian consists entirely of the kinetic term.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] If one considers a Riemannian manifold or a pseudo-Riemannian manifold, the Riemannian metric induces a linear isomorphism between the tangent and cotangent bundles.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Using this isomorphism, one can define a cometric.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] (In coordinates, the matrix defining the cometric is the inverse of the matrix defining the metric.) The solutions to the Hamilton–Jacobi equations for this Hamiltonian are then the same as the geodesics on the manifold.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] In particular, the Hamiltonian flow in this case is the same thing as the geodesic flow.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The existence of such solutions, and the completeness of the set of solutions, are discussed in detail in the article on geodesics.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] See also *Geodesics as Hamiltonian flows*.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] When the cometric is degenerate, then it is not invertible.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] In this case, one does not have a Riemannian manifold, as one does not have a metric.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] In the case where the cometric is degenerate at every point q of the configuration space manifold Q, so that the rank of the cometric is less than the dimension of the manifold Q, one has a sub-Riemannian manifold.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The Hamiltonian in this case is known as a **sub-Riemannian Hamiltonian**.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Every such Hamiltonian uniquely determines the cometric, and vice versa.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] This implies that every sub-Riemannian manifold is uniquely determined by its sub-Riemannian Hamiltonian, and that the converse is true: every sub-Riemannian manifold has a unique sub-Riemannian Hamiltonian.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The existence of sub-Riemannian geodesics is given by the Chow–Rashevskii theorem.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] The continuous, real-valued Heisenberg group provides a simple example of a sub-Riemannian manifold.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Hamiltonian systems can be generalized in various ways.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Instead of simply looking at the algebra of smooth functions over a symplectic manifold, Hamiltonian mechanics can be formulated on general commutative unital real Poisson algebras.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] A state is a continuous linear functional on the Poisson algebra (equipped with some suitable topology) such that for any element A of the algebra, *A*2 maps to a nonnegative real number.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] A further generalization is given by Nambu dynamics.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Hamilton's equations above work well for classical mechanics, but not for quantum mechanics, since the differential equations discussed assume that one can specify the exact position and momentum of the particle simultaneously at any point in time.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] However, the equations can be further generalized to then be extended to apply to quantum mechanics as well as to classical mechanics, through the deformation of the Poisson algebra over p and q to the algebra of Moyal brackets.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Specifically, the more general form of the Hamilton's equation reads ${\frac {\mathrm {d} f}{\mathrm {d} t}}=\left\{f,{\mathcal {H}}\right\}+{\frac {\partial f}{\partial t}},$ where f is some function of p and q, and H is the Hamiltonian.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] To find out the rules for evaluating a Poisson bracket without resorting to differential equations, see *Lie algebra*; a Poisson bracket is the name for the Lie bracket in a Poisson algebra.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] These Poisson brackets can then be extended to Moyal brackets comporting to an inequivalent Lie algebra, as proven by Hilbrand J.
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] Groenewold, and thereby describe quantum mechanical diffusion in phase space (See *Phase space formulation* and *Wigner–Weyl transform*).
[src:dynamical-systems/hamiltonian-mechanics] This more algebraic approach not only permits ultimately extending probability distributions in phase space to Wigner quasi-probability distributions, but, at the mere Poisson bracket classical setting, also provides more power in helping analyze the relevant conserved quantities in a system.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] In mathematics, in the study of dynamical systems with two-dimensional phase space, a **limit cycle** is a closed trajectory in phase space having the property that at least one other trajectory spirals into it either as time approaches infinity or as time approaches negative infinity.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] Such behavior is exhibited in some nonlinear systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] Limit cycles have been used to model the behavior of many real-world oscillatory systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] The study of limit cycles was initiated by Henri Poincaré (1854–1912).
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] We consider a two-dimensional dynamical system of the form $x'(t)=V(x(t))$ where $V:\mathbb {R} ^{2}\to \mathbb {R} ^{2}$ is a smooth function.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] A *trajectory* of this system is some smooth function $x(t)$ with values in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ which satisfies this differential equation.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] Such a trajectory is called *closed* (or *periodic*) if it is not constant but returns to its starting point, i.e. if there exists some $t_{0}>0$ such that $x(t+t_{0})=x(t)$ for all $t\in \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] An orbit is the image of a trajectory, a subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ .
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] A *closed orbit*, or *cycle*, is the image of a closed trajectory.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] A *limit cycle* is a cycle which is the limit set of some other trajectory.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] By the Jordan curve theorem, every closed trajectory divides the plane into two regions, the interior and the exterior of the curve.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] The corresponding statement holds for a trajectory in the interior that approaches the limit cycle for time approaching $-\infty$ , and also for trajectories in the exterior approaching the limit cycle.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] In the case where all the neighboring trajectories approach the limit cycle as time approaches infinity, it is called a *stable* or *attractive* limit cycle (ω-limit cycle).
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] If instead, all neighboring trajectories approach it as time approaches negative infinity, then it is an *unstable* limit cycle (α-limit cycle).
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] If there is a neighboring trajectory which spirals into the limit cycle as time approaches infinity, and another one which spirals into it as time approaches negative infinity, then it is a *semi-stable* limit cycle.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] There are also limit cycles that are neither stable, unstable nor semi-stable: for instance, a neighboring trajectory may approach the limit cycle from the outside, but the inside of the limit cycle is approached by a family of other cycles (which would not be limit cycles).
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] Stable limit cycles are examples of attractors.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] They imply self-sustained oscillations: the closed trajectory describes the perfect periodic behavior of the system, and any small perturbation from this closed trajectory causes the system to return to it, making the system stick to the limit cycle.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] Every closed trajectory contains within its interior a stationary point of the system, i.e. a point p where $V'(p)=0$ .
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] The Bendixson–Dulac theorem and the Poincaré–Bendixson theorem predict the absence or existence, respectively, of limit cycles of two-dimensional nonlinear dynamical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] Finding limit cycles, in general, is a very difficult problem.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] The number of limit cycles of a polynomial differential equation in the plane is the main object of the second part of Hilbert's sixteenth problem.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] It is unknown, for instance, whether there is any system $x'=V(x)$ in the plane where both components of V are quadratic polynomials of the two variables, such that the system has more than 4 limit cycles.
[src:dynamical-systems/limit-cycle] Limit cycles are important in many scientific applications where systems with self-sustained oscillations are modelled.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] The **phase space** of a physical system is the set of all possible physical states of the system when described by a given parameterization.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Each possible state corresponds uniquely to a point in the phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] For mechanical systems, the phase space usually consists of all possible values of the position and momentum parameters.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] It is the direct product of direct space and reciprocal space.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] The concept of phase space was developed in the late 19th century by Ludwig Boltzmann, Henri Poincaré, and Josiah Willard Gibbs.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] In a phase space, every degree of freedom or parameter of the system is represented as an axis of a multidimensional space; a one-dimensional system is called a phase line, while a two-dimensional system is called a phase plane.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] For every possible state of the system or allowed combination of values of the system's parameters, a point is included in the multidimensional space.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] The system's evolving state over time traces a path (a **phase-space trajectory** for the system) through the high-dimensional space.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] The phase-space trajectory represents the set of states compatible with starting from one particular initial condition, located in the full phase space that represents the set of states compatible with starting from *any* initial condition.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] As a whole, the phase diagram represents all that the system can be, and its shape can easily elucidate qualities of the system that might not be obvious otherwise.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] A phase space may contain a great number of dimensions.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] In classical mechanics, any choice of generalized coordinates *q**i* for the position (i.e. coordinates on configuration space) defines conjugate generalized momenta *p**i*, which together define co-ordinates on phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] The motion of an ensemble of systems in this space is studied by classical statistical mechanics.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] The local density of points in such systems obeys Liouville's theorem, and so can be taken as constant.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Within the context of a model system in classical mechanics, the phase-space coordinates of the system at any given time are composed of all of the system's dynamic variables.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Because of this, it is possible to calculate the state of the system at any given time in the future or the past, through integration of Hamilton's or Lagrange's equations of motion.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] For simple systems, there may be as few as one or two degrees of freedom.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] One degree of freedom occurs when one has an autonomous ordinary differential equation in a single variable, $dy/dt=f(y),$ with the resulting one-dimensional system being called a phase line, and the qualitative behaviour of the system being immediately visible from the phase line.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] The simplest non-trivial examples are the exponential growth model/decay (one unstable/stable equilibrium) and the logistic growth model (two equilibria, one stable, one unstable).
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] The phase space of a two-dimensional system is called a phase plane, which occurs in classical mechanics for a single particle moving in one dimension, and where the two variables are position and velocity.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] In this case, a sketch of the phase portrait may give qualitative information about the dynamics of the system, such as the limit cycle of the Van der Pol oscillator shown in the diagram.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Here the horizontal axis gives the position, and vertical axis the velocity.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] As the system evolves, its state follows one of the lines (trajectories) on the phase diagram.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] A plot of position and momentum variables as a function of time is sometimes called a **phase plot** or a **phase diagram**.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] However the latter expression, "phase diagram", is more usually reserved in the physical sciences for a diagram showing the various regions of stability of the thermodynamic phases of a chemical system, which consists of pressure, temperature, and composition.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] In mathematics, a phase portrait is a geometric representation of the orbits of a dynamical system in the phase plane.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Each set of initial conditions is represented by a different point or curve.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Phase portraits are an invaluable tool in studying dynamical systems.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] They consist of a plot of typical trajectories in the phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] This reveals information such as whether an attractor, a repellor or limit cycle is present for the chosen parameter value.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] The concept of topological equivalence is important in classifying the behaviour of systems by specifying when two different phase portraits represent the same qualitative dynamic behavior.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] An attractor is a stable point which is also called a "sink".
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] The repeller is considered as an unstable point, which is also known as a "source".
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] A phase portrait graph of a dynamical system depicts the system's trajectories (with arrows) and stable steady states (with dots) and unstable steady states (with circles) in a phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] In classical statistical mechanics (continuous energies) the concept of phase space provides a classical analog to the partition function (sum over states) known as the phase integral.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Instead of summing the Boltzmann factor over discretely spaced energy states (defined by appropriate integer quantum numbers for each degree of freedom), one may integrate over continuous phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Such integration essentially consists of two parts: integration of the momentum component of all degrees of freedom (momentum space) and integration of the position component of all degrees of freedom (configuration space).
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Once the phase integral is known, it may be related to the classical partition function by multiplication of a normalization constant representing the number of quantum energy states per unit phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] This normalization constant is simply the inverse of the Planck constant raised to a power equal to the number of degrees of freedom for the system.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] In quantum mechanics, the coordinates *p* and *q* of phase space normally become Hermitian operators in a Hilbert space.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] But they may alternatively retain their classical interpretation, provided functions of them compose in novel algebraic ways (through Groenewold's 1946 star product).
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] This is consistent with the uncertainty principle of quantum mechanics.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Every quantum mechanical observable corresponds to a unique function or distribution on phase space, and conversely, as specified by Hermann Weyl (1927) and supplemented by John von Neumann (1931); Eugene Wigner (1932); and, in a grand synthesis, by H.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Moyal (1949), these completed the foundations of the **phase-space formulation of quantum mechanics**, a complete and logically autonomous reformulation of quantum mechanics.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Expectation values in phase-space quantization are obtained isomorphically to tracing operator observables with the density matrix in Hilbert space: they are obtained by phase-space integrals of observables, with the Wigner quasi-probability distribution effectively serving as a measure.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] In thermodynamics and statistical mechanics contexts, the term "phase space" has two meanings: for one, it is used in the same sense as in classical mechanics.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] If a thermodynamic system consists of *N* particles, then a point in the 6*N*-dimensional phase space describes the dynamic state of every particle in that system, as each particle is associated with 3 position variables and 3 momentum variables.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] In this sense, as long as the particles are distinguishable, a point in phase space is said to be a microstate of the system.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] (For indistinguishable particles a microstate consists of a set of *N*! points, corresponding to all possible exchanges of the *N* particles.) *N* is typically on the order of the Avogadro number, thus describing the system at a microscopic level is often impractical.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] This leads to the use of phase space in a different sense.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] The phase space can also refer to the space that is parameterized by the *macroscopic* states of the system, such as pressure, temperature, etc.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] For instance, one may view the pressure–volume diagram or temperature–entropy diagram as describing part of this phase space.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] A point in this phase space is correspondingly called a macrostate.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] There may easily be more than one microstate with the same macrostate.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] For example, for a fixed temperature, the system could have many dynamic configurations at the microscopic level.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] When used in this sense, a phase is a region of phase space where the system in question is in, for example, the liquid phase, or solid phase, etc.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Since there are many more microstates than macrostates, the phase space in the first sense is usually a manifold of much larger dimensions than in the second sense.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Clearly, many more parameters are required to register every detail of the system down to the molecular or atomic scale than to simply specify, say, the temperature or the pressure of the system.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] Phase space is extensively used in nonimaging optics, the branch of optics devoted to illumination.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] It is also an important concept in Hamiltonian optics.
[src:dynamical-systems/phase-space] In medicine and bioengineering, the phase space method is used to visualize multidimensional physiological responses.
